snippet.textDisplay:
Ah yes, the other place that the Try Guys went on their international tour dates. I had the opportunity to try Laksa and sweets with durian inside at an Indonesian food market in Cambridge, MA just before the winter holidays. Laksa is warming, although I wish I had some baked goods to remedy the overly fishy flavor of the broth. Zach is right though; fresh durian likely doesn't leave a fermented after taste in your mouth, which is what the durian custard sweet did for me. Mango with garlic and herbs? Hmm... sounds delicious to me. Maybe that can be one of my goals for 2020, along with finding a steady, paying job: try fresh durian.
P.S. Orchids are my favorite flower, so much variety in color, patterning, size, and petal shape and yet very recognizable to casual viewers too. To see Eugene, Ned, Wes and the others there in that garden... not going to lie. Part of me is wishing it would hurry up and get to March so I can go to the Boston Flower show.

snippet.textDisplay:
Actually, Jewel only opened this year. Changi itself is AMAZING. There's a hotel within the terminal itself in case you have a long layover and want a nap or shower. Then there's the free cinema in T3 that I've personally used to take a break in many times. Plus shopping. And the food. Oh my god the food.

But if you're in Singapore long enough (at least 6hrs), you already have your boarding pass for your next flight so you don't have to check-in again and your nationality doesn't require a visa, go through immigration, jump in a taxi and go to any of the places the guys went to. Just be back at least an hour before your next flight.

snippet.textDisplay:
No hate here but I feel like a lot of food like nasi lemak, chicken rice, laksa, prata (roti canai), durian and many other food is labelled as Singaporean food, and Singaporean food only
As much as it is Singapore Food, its also Malaysian food, it is not just unique to Singapore
The racial culture, having many different races living together in one country, that is also in Malaysia too.
Almost everything in this video I can relate to Malaysia... I'm just sad that many tourists don't know or realise that.

Again no hate, to those that don't know, I hope this educates you guys. I love the try guys!
